window.docContents[238].resolve({"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group--Nonzero-Fractional-Ideals-Form-an-Abelian-Group":{"contents":"For a Dedekind domain  () with fraction field , the nonzero\nfractional ideals () form an abelian group under multiplication, with\nidentity  and inverse ; including the zero ideal,\n is a commutative group with zero. This group is free\nabelian on the set of nonzero prime ideals of .\n\nThe only nontrivial axiom is that every nonzero fractional ideal  is invertible, i.e.\n. mathlib packages this as IsDedekindDomainInv, the statement that\n for all nonzero , which is equivalent to  being Dedekind\n(isDedekindDomain_iff_isDedekindDomainInv); the commGroupWithZero instance then reads off\nmul_inv_cancel from this together with inv_zero and the division-as-multiplication law. The\nfree-abelian structure follows because invertibility lets one cancel primes, so the unique\nfactorisation of ideals () extends to a -valued\nvaluation at each prime, giving an isomorphism with the free abelian group .\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory\u0009Fractional ideals and the class group","header":"3.3.2. Nonzero Fractional Ideals Form an Abelian Group","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group--Nonzero-Fractional-Ideals-Form-an-Abelian-Group"}});